e lyric voice and distinguishes her as a poetic innovator who would be widely imitated by female writers in Italy and Europe in the sixteenth century. After three centuries of relative neglect, this new edition promises to restore Colonna to her rightful place at the forefront of female cultural production in the Renaissance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPOETRY / General.2bisacsh  apoetry, literature, women writers, female authors, authorship, italy, renaissance, gender, feminism, literati, petrarchan sonnets, form, verse, chastity, piety, femininity, social norms, michelangelo buonarroti, friendship, innovation, europe, bilingual, translation, virtue, public sphere, cultural production, vittoria colonna, celebrity, fame.1 aBrundin, Abigail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Margaret L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabil, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022611391340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226113937423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226113937/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles